amaste madam,


I will share a few freewheeling thoughts.

In the beginning=
, it is useful to have an intellectual understanding. Reading books and tal=
king to people tells us what is permanent and what is not and how to think =
and act.

But, just reading books and having an intellectual understanding =
of liberation is not jnana yoga - it is merely an interest in it. To be a j=
nana yogi, one must imbibe that wisdom into one's actions, thoughts and eve=
n instincts, i.e. one must overcome attraction and aversion to things and d=
evelop equal vision. But, there are innate instincts from millions of lives=
 that cannot be overcome just like that. It takes time and practice.

Now, =
different circumstances may trigger our instincts differently. So one may a=
void some circumstances and actions that trigger more troublesome instincts=
 and deal with less troublesome instincts first. One can first try to overc=
omes the easier instincts.

In the beginning, one has theoretical knowledge=
 and intellectual clarity. Then one engages in daily practices that calm th=
e mind so that there is some chance of resisting instincts during moments o=
f crisis and challenge that come later in the day. :-) Of course, this prac=
tice may be meditation or homam or even reading a spiritual book or contemp=
lation of one's motives!

As one practices, one is trying to put intellectu=
al understanding to use. Over time, one's conditioning is overcome and one'=
s neural networks are re-programmed. One becomes wiser (i.e. theoretical un=
derstanding is imbibed into thinking and instincts).


Then one may learn t=
o resist circumstances and actions that one avoided dealing with before (be=
cause they trigger instincts too difficult to resist).

Though one in pursu=
it of wisdom may avoid some actions, because they trigger irresistible inst=
incts, a jnani after some stage does not run after or away from specific ac=
tions. He has no agendas or desires and deals with any circumstances that c=
ome one's way based on momentum from before and deals with them.

*        =
*        *

As Vasishtha said, action and wisdom go hand in hand. Actions h=
elp you imbibe wisdom into your instincts. Wisdom enables better actions.

=
Upanishads give a nice analogy. One with only action and no knowledge is li=
ke a blind person running into a forest fire. One with only knowledge and n=
o action, is like a legless person who helplessly looks at the forest fire =
rushing at one. He knows it will kill him, but he can't do anything about i=
t!

A bird cannot fly by flapping one wing. But, at the same time, there is=
 no formula for how to fly. A bird starts flapping both wings arbitrarily a=
nd yet does not fly. As it tries, oneday its neural networks are programmed=
 to send the right signals to right nerves in the right order and it just f=
lies!

Similarly, one cannot free oneself by just stressing knowledge (inte=
llectual understanding) or physical/mental action. One engages in both arbi=
trarily, without the right balance, one oneday one's instincts are correctl=
y programmed to allow a takeoff!

*        *        *

Meditating in front =
of fire is powerful and transformational. Really, all you need is a bright =
fire in which you imagine divinity. Some procedures and devised to give tha=
t sense of sacredness and divinity, but all you really need is fire.

But, =
if homam is not attractive to one, that is fine. One can just meditate. Or =
just chant God's name. Or just read books. Or contemplate. But add some new=
 practices that calm the mind, if you want to re-wire and re-program your b=
rain. Brain is happy to persist with habits. Breaking old habits often requ=
ires creating new habits (that are hopefully less problematic).

Spending a=
 decent amount of time (e.g. half hour or one hour) is better than just 5 m=
in, though something is better than nothing.

Best regards,

Narasimha
